## Step 2: Deploy Backend to Railway

### 2.1 Create Railway Account
Go to [https://railway.app](https://railway.app) and sign up/login.

### 2.2 Create a New Project
1. Click **"New Project"**
2. Select **"Deploy from GitHub repo"**
3. Choose `Osinachi-cloud/sms_backend`

### 2.3 Add PostgreSQL Database
1. In your Railway project, click **"New"**
2. Select **"Database"** → **"Add PostgreSQL"**
3. Railway auto-creates the database and injects `DATABASE_URL` into your service

### 2.4 Configure Environment Variables
Go to your `sms_backend` service → **Variables** tab. Add these:

| Variable | Value | Required |
|----------|-------|----------|
| `DATABASE_URL` | Auto-injected by Railway | Yes |
| `JWT_SECRET` | Generate: `openssl rand -base64 64` | Yes |
| `PAYSTACK_SECRET_KEY` | `sk_test_...` or `sk_live_...` | Yes |
| `PAYSTACK_PUBLIC_KEY` | `pk_test_...` or `pk_live_...` | No |
| `PAYSTACK_CALLBACK_URL` | `https://your-frontend.vercel.app/payments/verify` | Yes |
| `OPENAI_API_KEY` | `sk-...` | No |
| `CORS_ALLOWED_ORIGINS` | `https://your-frontend.vercel.app` | Yes |
| `SPRING_PROFILES_ACTIVE` | `prod` | Yes |
| `SERVER_PORT` | `8080` | Yes |

### 2.5 Deploy
Railway auto-detects the `Dockerfile` and builds it. Your backend URL will be something like:
```
https://schoolsaas-api.up.railway.app
```

### 2.6 Verify Backend Health
```bash
curl https://your-railway-url.up.railway.app/api/health
```
Expected response: `{"status":"UP"}`

